Individuals with autism may find maintaining eye contact uncomfortable or overwhelming, which can affect social interactions. This aversion to eye contact is often due to the intense sensory input it involves, making it hard to process simultaneously with conversation. Seeking time alone is another common trait, as social situations can be exhausting and overstimulating. Personal space provides a refuge where individuals can decompress and engage in self-soothing activities, away from the unpredictability of social demands. Language comprehension in autism can be notably literal. Metaphors, idioms, and sarcasm are often taken at face value, as the nuanced and abstract nature of these expressions can be challenging to interpret. This literal understanding reflects a different cognitive processing style, emphasizing concrete over abstract thinking. Sensory hypersensitivity means that ordinary stimuli, such as lights, sounds, textures, or smells, can be overwhelmingly intense. This heightened sensitivity can lead to discomfort or distress in environments that are otherwise considered normal, necessitating careful management to ensure comfort and reduce anxiety. These features collectively illustrate the diverse and individualised nature of autism, shaping how each person experiences and interacts with the world. #autism #asd #autismawareness #mentalhealth #psychiatry #psychiatrist

What are Gestalt phrases?  A gestalt is an intonation rich long or short phrase that to the gestalt language processor, conveys a very specific meaning. Most gestalt phrases are emotion based and most of the time do not seem to relate to the situation at hand. They are all used to process, communicate a need, or express emotions when other forms of communication are challenging. They can also be self-soothing or self-stimulation behavior, providing comfort or familiarity in stressful or overwhelming situations. Asperger syndrome was a term used to describe a developmental disorder on the autism spectrum characterised by significant difficulties in social interaction and nonverbal communication, alongside restricted and repetitive patterns of behavior and interests. Individuals with Asperger syndrome typically had average to above-average intelligence and did not exhibit a delay in language development.  People with Asperger syndrome were said to have focused interests, sometimes to an intense degree, and may have excelled in specific fields or hobbies.  In 2013, the DSM-5 reclassified Asperger syndrome under the broader category of Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD), which now encompasses various conditions previously diagnosed separately. There is also significant controversy surrounding Hans Asperger, after whom the condition was named. #asperger #autism #asd #mentalhealth #psychiatry #psychiatrist

What are Gestalt phrases?  A gestalt is an intonation rich long or short phrase that to the gestalt language processor, conveys a very specific meaning. Most gestalt phrases are emotion based and most of the time do not seem to relate to the situation at hand. They are all used to process, communicate a need, or express emotions when other forms of communication are challenging. They can also be self-soothing or self-stimulation behavior, providing comfort or familiarity in stressful or overwhelming situations. This video is aimed at beginner Golfers who might find themselves overwhelmed by the amount of information online regarding where to play the ball in your stance for each club. Golf is confusing when you first start out, so let's make one of the first fundamentals you should learn simple. I tell my new students just to remember 3 ball positions: Middle, an inch forward of Middle, and in line with your lead heel. The corresponding clubs match each position as outlined in the video. You will find success using these positions for these clubs not to mention it is one less thing in the game to make complex! AOA Aspirants! These are the 10 most basic things you need to know about the NUMS exam. 1. What is NUMS and NUMS MDCAT? NUMS stands for National University of Medical Sciences. It's a medical university that has 13 private colleges (Including 5 institutes of dentistry) under it and 1 Public college. In order to get admission in these colleges, Nums conducts its OWN SEPARATE ENTRY TEST called the Nums MDCAT. 2. How is it different from normal MDCAT?  Provincial MDCAT and Nums MDCAT are two separate tests. Nums test is only for Nums affiliated colleges, while provincial MDCAT is for the rest of the public and private colleges of Pakistan. 3. Is it important to pass provincial MDCAT for getting admission in Nums colleges? No, passing provincial mdcat is not compulsory. Only NUMS MDCAT will be counted. 4. What are the names of Nums affiliated colleges? Public: Army Medical College Rawalpindi Private: CMH Lahore Medical College CMH Kharian Medical College CMH Bahawalpur Institute of medical sciences CMH Multan Institute of medical sciences Fazaia medical college Islamabad Fazaia ruth Pfau medical college Karachi  Bahria medical and dental college Qeutta institute of medical sciences (QIMS)  Karachi Institute of Medical Sciences (KIMS)   Wah Medical College, Wah Cantt.  Foundation University Medical College Islamabad  Nust school of health sciences Hitech institute of Medical Sciences 5. What is the syllabus and paper pattern? The syllabus is comparatively easier and less as compared to provincial MDCAT. Syllabus is available on Nums official website. Paper pattern includes: 150 MCQs from Biology, Chem, Physics and English (2.5 hours) 100 MCQs Psychological portion (30 minutes) Note: Only 5% of this portion will be counted in your exam. Why Autism in Women Is Often Overlooked: Understanding the Differences in Diagnosis Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) can be easier to diagnose in adults, but women often go undiagnosed or misdiagnosed due to differences in how autism presents. Hereâ€™s why: Men with autism tend to fit the more stereotypical patterns of ASD, making their diagnosis more straightforward. Their struggles with emotional literacy and special interests are often more obvious. Women, however, often have more subtle or hidden traits. They may appear to master emotional literacy better and their special interests may not stand out as much, leading to a missed diagnosis. Women on the spectrum tend to show more variation in their special interests, whereas men may gravitate toward specific industries or skill sets, making their autism more noticeable. Understanding these gender differences is crucial for improving the diagnosis and support of women with autism, who often face unique challenges in a world that doesnâ€™t recognize their experiences as easily. Screen time can have specific negative impacts on children with autism, including: 1. **Social Skills**: Excessive screen time may limit opportunities for social interaction, which is crucial for children with autism to develop and practice social skills. 2. **Sensory Overload**: Screen time can contribute to sensory overload for children with autism, as they may be more sensitive to visual and auditory stimuli. This overload can lead to increased anxiety and difficulty in processing information. 3. **Rigid Behaviors**: Extended screen time can reinforce rigid behaviors and repetitive interests, which are common characteristics of autism, potentially limiting exposure to new experiences and activities. 4. **Communication Development**: Excessive screen time may interfere with the development of communication skills, including verbal and nonverbal communication, which are already areas of challenge for many children with autism. 5. **Attention Difficulties**: Children with autism may have difficulties with attention and focus, and excessive screen time can exacerbate these issues, making it harder for them to engage in other activities and learn from their environment. The weather has been HOT where I am, so sometimes indoor interventions are necessary-  When working with pediatric clients I love the versatility of obstacle courses. There are SO MANY THINGS that can be targeted for skill development and SO MUCH FUN that is possible. My favorite part is encouraging children to help design their own parts of the obstacle course.  Here are some of my favorite home materials/ideas for how they may be used - but donâ€™t let this list limit your creativity!!  -Crash pad (jumping/crashing/proprioceptive input) -Trampoline (jumping, strength, balance) -Cones (Bilateral coordination, planning, boundaries) -Dress up clothes (ADLs, motor skills, social participation)  -Balls (visual motor integration, strengthening) -Hula hoops (hopping, weight-shifting/balance, boundaries)  -Slide (climbing, risky play, spatial orientation)  -Bean bags (heavy work, hand-eye coordination)  -Tunnels (crawling, body awareness, sensory needs)  -Scooter board (laying in prone (on belly) WITH squigz using to pull, push = proprioceptive input, motor planning, strength) -Laundry Basket (throwing into, scooping out, carrying, heavy work)  -Wobble cushion (stepping stone, balance)  -Balance beam (balance, visual motor skills) -sit and spin (sensory needs, strengthening, vestibular input) #theearthyot #occupationaltherapy #obstaclecourse #pediatrics #sensory #play #childdevelopment #motorskills #gradstudent #challenge #momsoftiktok #staycool #letsplay

We didnâ€™t speak the same language so they continued along without understanding my repeated â€œnoâ€™sâ€. Never in my life have I felt so out of control and so disconnected from my body.  I was never informed that this would be how I would have to disembark the plane, and it never crossed my mind given that this airport DOES use jet bridges. In fact, all of the other planes around us were pulled up to them.  I love sharing my travels as a wheelchair user because I truly believe that there is so much in this world is accessible and I want to inspire people to experience that. an aperitif for the olive oil obsessed ğŸ«’  olive oil vermouth | test batch (2 servings) â€¢ 1/4 cup / 60ml high-quality extra virgin olive oil  â€¢ 1 cup / 250ml dry vermouth notes:  â€¢ you donâ€™t need a top-tier finishing oil but the more fragrant and flavourful the olive oil is, the more fragrant and flavourful the vermouth will be. a good indication of what olive oil to use is if you can enjoy the olive oil on its own drizzled over bread. it must be 100% pure olive oil otherwise it will not freeze.  â€¢ important: use a fresh bottle of vermouth! vermouth is a fortified wine and begins to oxidize once opened. if its been sitting on your shelf for months, itâ€™s time for a new bottle. always refrigerate your vermouth after opening and consume, ideally, within a month.  technique (24h infusion):  â€¢ pour olive oil and vermouth into a jar. close the lid and shake until well incorporated. leave to infuse at room temp for 1 hour. naturally, the oil will float to the top so remember to give it a good shake every 20mins for that first hour. â€¢ give it another shake before moving the jar to the fridge. shake whenever you remember.  â€¢ after the 24h infusion time, turn the jar upside down and freeze for another 2 hours. all freezers are different and yours may need a little less or more time. the goal is to freeze the olive oil but not the vermouth so that they can be easily separated.  â€¢ the olive oil should now be a solid disk, allowing you to easily pour the vermouth over a coffee filter for a final straining. the finished vermouth should have a fragrant olive oil scent and silky smooth mouthfeel.  drink chilled on its own or,  over ice for a slow dilution or,  highball with some sparkling water.  optional but a nice touch:  make some olive + olive brine ice cubes to get those dirty martini feels ğŸ¸  #extravirginoliveoil #oliveoil #vermouth #aperitif #recipe #summerdrink #recipeoftheday #recipedeveloper

Pasta in Italy IS different! .    I mean, authentic food always tastes better, right?! And many times different ingredients and drying processes are used which CAN impact things like gluten structure and amounts. If you have a gluten intolerance, yes, you might notice a difference in digestion! .    But there is also the fact that with decreased stress, slower paces of life, etc. digestion can improve. I'm not saying intolerances aren't real or that if you just stress less they'll go away. Absolutely NOT! But, for example, I used to get a tummy ache when I ate ice cream because it was a stress tummy ache over feeling guilty and like I shouldn't. Is that the case for everyone? No! When should you use the term high functioning autism?  The majority of autistic people have been advocating for years to not use functioning labels. This is for a couple of important reasons. One being that we all have strengths and weaknesses just like anyone else. so we might be very "high functioning" in one area but need a lot of support in another.  The other reason is that functioning labels cause a lot more harm to the autistic community than they do good. often if someone is labeled low functioning, people just write them off and they often don't qualify for services that they might benefit from because of the low functioning label it is assumed they can't benefit from them. on the flip side of that, those who are considered high functioning, often still need a lot of support for certain things and are often denied help because "your functioning you don't need help you need to try harder" #autism #autistic #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #functioninglabels

When should you use the term high functioning autism?  The majority of autistic people have been advocating for years to not use functioning labels. This is for a couple of important reasons. One being that we all have strengths and weaknesses just like anyone else. so we might be very "high functioning" in one area but need a lot of support in another.  The other reason is that functioning labels cause a lot more harm to the autistic community than they do good. often if someone is labeled low functioning, people just write them off and they often don't qualify for services that they might benefit from because of the low functioning label it is assumed they can't benefit from them. on the flip side of that, those who are considered high functioning, often still need a lot of support for certain things and are often denied help because "your functioning you don't need help you need to try harder" #autism #autistic #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #functioninglabels

While the behaviors are often associated with Autism Spectrum Disorder (#ASD), it is an oversimplification to view them as definitive or exclusive symptoms. These behaviors reflect complex interactions of sensory, cognitive and social processing differences that vary widely among individuals with ASD. Planning Conversations People with ASD may meticulously plan conversations as a strategy to manage social anxiety and ensure predictability in interactions. This behavior is often a response to the discomfort they feel in social situations due to sensory overresponsivity (SOR) and the associated anxiety. Clumsiness or bumping into walls can be attributed to proprioceptive and vestibular processing difficulties common in ASD. These sensory challenges affect balance and spatial awareness, leading to increased incidents of physical clumsiness. Inflexibility and distress over changes in routine are hallmark traits of ASD. This behavior is linked to an intolerance of uncertainty, which can exacerbate anxiety and lead to extreme responses to deviations from expected plans. Sensory sensitivities, particularly to tactile stimuli, are common in individuals with ASD. These sensitivities can cause strong aversions to certain textures, such as microfiber, due to the heightened or altered sensory processing in these individuals. Discomfort with physical affection, such as hugging, often stems from sensory overresponsivity as well. Deep pressure touch, which can be soothing for some, may be overwhelming for individuals with ASD, leading them to avoid hugs and other forms of physical touch. These behaviors are manifestations of the unique #sensoryprocessing and social interaction challenges faced by individuals with ASD. Understanding these behaviors helps in providing better support and interventions tailored to the needs of those with #autism.

People who struggle with hoarding have difficulty letting go of possessions. Their living spaces become cluttered, disorganized, and often unfit for living in. While there can be different root causes of hoarding, one that is not very well known is that hoarding can be a behavior exhibited by people who are on the autism spectrum, including people with masked autism. In these cases, hoarding results from issues with emotional regulation, sensory regulation, and executive functioning. Have you heard of Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes/Hypermobility Spectrum Disorders (EDS/HSD) or Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)?  Considerable interest has arisen concerning the high rate of cooccurence between hereditary connective tissue disorders such as the Ehlers-Danlos syndromes (EDS)/hypermobility spectrum disorders (HSD) and Autism. The overlap between these two spectrum conditions, including neurobehavioural, psychiatric, and neurological commonalities, shared peripheral neuropathies and neuropathologies, and similar autonomic and immune dysregulation suggest that EDS/HSD may represent a subtype of Autism. Today we are joined by Dr. Emily Casanova. Emily has a research background in neurobiology, developmental biology with particular foci on Autism, and connective tissue disorders like EDS and HSD. She is passionate about patient advocacy for individuals with chronic and/or rare illnesses and lived experience of Autism, EDS, and HSD.    Emily is featured in Module 3 of The Autism & Neurodiversity MasterClass where we deep dive into what Autism actually is, the science, the history, Spikey Skills and Colour Wheels, the Autism and ADHD overlap, PDA and a number of co-occuring conditions like EDS, HSD and POTS. Accessible Rest for Neurodivergent Individuals > Self-Regulation > Levels If you are neurodivergent, have chronic fatigue, fibromyalgia, POTS, PTSD, cPTSD or any other nervous system dysfunction or irregularity this video might help explain why you canâ€™t seem to access typical regulation strategies.  Here is a summary: Level 1: Focus on the environment and indulgence. FOG = Fear, obligation, guilt. You want the following to be â€œFOG-freeâ€. Once you can access these strategies FOG-free, you can begin to shift into Level 2 Level 1 Examples:  Yummy food Cat videos Scrolling funny videos Calming video games like Stardew Valley or Minecraft Aromatherapy  Soft blankets Cozy Jammies Level 2: Focus on body-specific strategies that give vestibular or proprioceptive input. Think: Deep pressure. Once you can access these AND include Level 1 strategies simultaneously, start shifting into Level 3. Level 2 Examples: Deep stretching Massage Swinging Walk in nature Water (swimming, bath, etc.) Weighted blanket You will want to consistently start at Level 1 and work your way through the levels each time you need to regulate. Did you know when choosing between doing a flexi rod set on wet hair versus blow-dried hair, there are a few key differences to consider: Flexi Rod Set on Wet Hair: -Better Definition: Curls tend to be more defined when set on wet hair. -Longer Lasting: Wet sets generally last longer because the hair dries into the shape of the curls. -Longer Drying Time: Wet hair takes longer to dry, especially if air-drying. This can be inconvenient. - Shrinkage: Wet hair tends to shrink as it dries, which may result in shorter curls than expected. Flexi Rod Set on Blow-Dried Hair: -Quicker Drying Time: Hair is already dry, so the setting process is faster. -More Length: Blow-dried hair generally has less shrinkage, resulting in longer-looking curls. -Smoother Finish: Blow-drying can help achieve a smoother look by reducing frizz before setting the hair. -Less Definition: Curls may be less defined compared to a wet set. -Shorter Lasting: Curls may not last as long as those set on wet hair. Have you heard of Ehlers-Danlos Syndromes/Hypermobility Spectrum Disorders (EDS/HSD) or Postural Orthostatic Tachycardia Syndrome (POTS)?  Considerable interest has arisen concerning the high rate of cooccurence between hereditary connective tissue disorders such as the Ehlers-Danlos syndromes (EDS)/hypermobility spectrum disorders (HSD) and Autism. The overlap between these two spectrum conditions, including neurobehavioural, psychiatric, and neurological commonalities, shared peripheral neuropathies and neuropathologies, and similar autonomic and immune dysregulation suggest that EDS/HSD may represent a subtype of Autism. Today we are joined by Dr. Emily Casanova. Emily has a research background in neurobiology, developmental biology with particular foci on Autism, and connective tissue disorders like EDS and HSD. She is passionate about patient advocacy for individuals with chronic and/or rare illnesses and lived experience of Autism, EDS, and HSD.    Emily is featured in Module 3 of The Autism & Neurodiversity MasterClass where we deep dive into what Autism actually is, the science, the history, Spikey Skills and Colour Wheels, the Autism and ADHD overlap, PDA and a number of co-occuring conditions like EDS, HSD and POTS. What you can do to support them: The key is to support or ask for help in a way that doesn't feel overwhelming or exhausting for them. Here are some examples: - I was thinking of watching a new movie tonight, and I'd love your company. Do you mind if I come over with snacks? We can just relax and enjoy the it together. - I'm trying out different tea blends and could really use your help to choose the best one. Want to join me for a tea tasting session? - Thereâ€™s a new cafe that opened up nearby, and I heard they have great coffee. Want to check it out with me? My treat! - It's a great evening for a drive. How about we just cruise around for a bit while listening to some good music? I can pick you up in an hour! Keep in mind that, sometimes, they might not be up to hosting at their place if they think itâ€™s untidy, and going out might seem overwhelming if it requires a lot of preparation or too much energy. So opt for activities that are simple and enjoyable â€” things that won't drain their energy but will genuinely make them feel included and valued. This way, you offer support without adding pressure. Hereâ€™s how this stress hormone wreaks havoc on your rest and disrupts your natural circadian rhythm: 1. It Keeps You Up at Night: Elevated cortisol makes you feel alert and restless, making it hard to fall and stay asleep. 2. It Increases Anxiety: High cortisol amps up anxiety, causing your mind to race with worries and what-ifs. 3. Frequent Bathroom Trips: Cortisol can increase fluid retention and urinary urgency, making you get up multiple times to pee. 4. 3 AM Wake-Ups: Cortisol levels can spike in the early morning hours, jolting you awake and making it hard to fall back asleep. 5. It Disrupts Circadian Rhythm: Cortisol naturally peaks in the morning to help you wake up and gradually decreases throughout the day. When dysregulated, you feel tired during the day but wide awake at night, disrupting your natural sleep-wake cycle. When should you use the term high functioning autism?  The majority of autistic people have been advocating for years to not use functioning labels. This is for a couple of important reasons. One being that we all have strengths and weaknesses just like anyone else. so we might be very "high functioning" in one area but need a lot of support in another.  The other reason is that functioning labels cause a lot more harm to the autistic community than they do good. often if someone is labeled low functioning, people just write them off and they often don't qualify for services that they might benefit from because of the low functioning label it is assumed they can't benefit from them. on the flip side of that, those who are considered high functioning, often still need a lot of support for certain things and are often denied help because "your functioning you don't need help you need to try harder" #autism #autistic #autismacceptance #autismawareness #autistictiktok #autisticcreator #functioninglabels

People with ADHD are more likely to have trouble with sensory processing in general, but auditory processing issues are especially common.  People with auditory processing issues donâ€™t have any problem with their ability to hear. But things start to break down once the sound goes from ear to brain.  That means that even though we may physically hear what someone says, it may take us a while to actually process and understand it.  Studies have shown that people with ADHD are more likely to have trouble distinguishing between sounds and filtering out irrelevant sounds so they can focus on the important ones (for example, ignoring background noise in a restaurant so they can focus on a conversation). Interestingly, studies have suggested that treatment with stimulant medications may restore auditory processing abilities in some people with ADHD. If you have trouble with this stuff, you may be able to request that your school or workplace provide written instructions in addition to verbal. Most schools and workplaces are able to accommodate this and it can be really helpful! Note: we do not diagnose ADHD based on auditory processing issues alone. ADHD is not the only cause of auditory processing issues and not everyone with ADHD will have auditory processing issues. #adhd #adhdproblems #adhdmemes

Why Autism in Women Is Often Overlooked: Understanding the Differences in Diagnosis Autism Spectrum Disorder (ASD) can be easier to diagnose in adults, but women often go undiagnosed or misdiagnosed due to differences in how autism presents. Hereâ€™s why: Men with autism tend to fit the more stereotypical patterns of ASD, making their diagnosis more straightforward. Their struggles with emotional literacy and special interests are often more obvious. Women, however, often have more subtle or hidden traits. They may appear to master emotional literacy better and their special interests may not stand out as much, leading to a missed diagnosis. Women on the spectrum tend to show more variation in their special interests, whereas men may gravitate toward specific industries or skill sets, making their autism more noticeable. Understanding these gender differences is crucial for improving the diagnosis and support of women with autism, who often face unique challenges in a world that doesnâ€™t recognize their experiences as easily. Learn more about how autism presents differently in women and why these differences matter for proper diagnosis and support. #autisminwomen  #autismawareness  #Neurodivergent
